abstract: I have read with considerable interest your editorial headed "The German Bogy," and I am bound to say that I think Prof. Hershey has truly grasped the possibilities of the future international situation. abstract: GRAND JUNCTION, Col., June 3. -- An immense snow bank, sixty feet deep, lying on the slope of Mount Ellott, a 13,000-foot peak in Southwestern Colorado, has melted within the last forty-eight hours and an immense column of steam is rising from the spot. The cloud of steam is visible for miles. It is believed by those familiar with the mountain that the phenomenon is caused by a volcanic disturbance.

abstract: WINNIPEG, Manitoba, June 4. -- In a fifteen-mile race here to-night, Henry St. Yves completely outclassed J.D. Marsh, the Winnipeg man who won the Toronto Marathon recently. abstract: Redeemed, Renewed, Replenished, and Elected are among the baptismal names found in Sussex by E.V. Lucas, but are they to be compared, these single participles, with the Massachusetts name of the early nineteenth century, Emma Jemima Grace-Peace Mercy? Occasionally they called her Emma, but the smallest dereliction from the strict virtue required of the early nineteenth century babe called forth the whole five names, followed by the two family names which also belonged to her.

abstract: Can age be a mere matter of opinion? I think so. A woman of 83, never robust, unable from adverse circumstances to coddle herself, and compelled to be versatile in her own field, as well as, alas! in the field of the so-called stronger sex, might well have reached the acme of physical and mental decay. I am just what I have described, and I have lost neither courage, hope, nor activity.

abstract: Brooklyn showed the way to New York yesterday afternoon in the intercity relay race, which was a feature of the games of the Acorn Athletic Association at Hawthorne Field, Brooklyn. abstract: As Socialism would abolish competition, what effect will it have upon invention? Mr. Blatchford, in "Merrie England," tells us that inventors will be rewarded "by a medal and the naming of the process after its inventor, and the invention becomes the property of the State." Thus Socialists assume that invention will go on under Socialism as now, and that inventors will be satisfied with a medal.

abstract: IT WAS a still tropic morning in 1920. The enemy's fleets, by prearrangement, appeared on both the Atlantic and the Pacific sides of the Panama Canal at the same time. On shore there were no signs of activity; no indications that the enemy was expected, and although the officers on the approaching battleships swept the shores with their glasses they could perceive no fortifications.

abstract: WASHINGTON, June 5. -- James B. abstract: SOUTHAMPTON, L.I., June 5. -- Second only to Newport as the most popular Summer resort along the entire Atlantic seaboard among New York's fashionable social set, Southampton is rapidly assuming the regalia coincident with the season of recreative pastime. abstract: Prince HENRY of Prussia, representing his august brother, congratulated the Navy League yesterday upon its good work. abstract: HAMILTON, Bermuda, June 8. -- So far as can be figured to-night, the schooner Margaret, owned by George S. abstract: In his native village in Southern Germany half a century ago Fritz Hauser fell in love with the village belle and spent much of his time at her home, bringing her presents and watching her as she worked at the spinning wheel. abstract: BUFFALO, June 8. -- A paper by Dr. Boris D. abstract: The human race, Mr. Fries contends, suffers no ill-effects from its meat-eating habits. Yet it is generally acknowledged that the human race dies very prematurely -- so prematurely, in fact, that a full third of people's lives is cut off entirely. It is generally recognized by biologists that any animal should live five times the length of its period of maturity; a dog matures at 2 and dies at 10.

abstract: SPRING LAKE, N.J., June 10, 2 A.M. -- Sixty men and women, guests of The Breakers, one of the biggest hotels on the water front here, narrowly escaped in their nightclothes when fire started in the big wooden structure late to-night. Every one in the hotel was asleep and the blaze had gained great headway before John H. Eckel of 373 Park Place, Brooklyn, discovered it and ran to the hotel to give the alarm.

abstract: WAMSUTTER, Wyo., June 9. -- The prospects for to-day's walk are not very encouraging. The wind is blowing and it is very evident it will rain again. abstract: PARIS, June 9. -- The body of James A. Richmond, once a traction magnate in New York, will be sent to America on Saturday. Mr. Richmond had lived at the Grand Hotel in Paris for many years. He had been ailing for several weeks, and took to his bed on Saturday. The trouble was believed to be peritonitis following an attack of appendicitis.

abstract: HAMILTON, Bermuda, June 9. -- All of the power boats in the race from Gravesend Bay, New York, to this port reached here to-day. Richmond Levering's Heather, the scratch boat in the contest, was first to cross the finish line off St. David's Head. This was at 1:30 A.M., and she was far enough in advance of the others to overcome their, time allowance, thereby winning, the Bermuda challenge cup and the prize of. $1,000.

abstract: NEW HAVEN, Conn., June 9. -- A safe deposit box, rented in the name of Frederick H. abstract: LONDON, June 10. -- The Imperial Press Conference has brought its business sessions to a temporary close, and the delegates will spend the next fortnight in sightseeing. abstract: LONDON, June 12 -- "Much cry and little wool" might well be the epitaph of the Imperial Press Conference held this week in London. abstract: ALBANY, June 12. -- The year 1908, following the financial panic, witnessed a marked reversal of conditions in the mineral industries of the State, according to statistics compiled by State Geologist John M. Clarke in co-operation with the United States Geological Survey. To the Prosperity and steady expansion that had so long obtained in these industries succeeded general depression and contraction, which continued with little or no relief throughout the twelve months.

abstract: The non-magnetic yacht Carnegie, in the construction of which practically no iron, steel, or other magnetic metal was used, was launched in Tebo's Yacht Basin, at the foot of Twenty-third Street, Brooklyn, yesterday afternoon. abstract: A writer in The Forum divulges the fact that GEORGE MEREDITH found HENRY JAMES'S books "hard reading." There is no reason why the revelation should surprise us. They are "hard reading," assuredly, and because MEREDITH'S books are equally hard we were not justified in supposing that he possessed powers of comprehension and interpretation so far superior to those of his fellow-men as to enable him to take in the meaning of JAMES at a glance.

abstract: ITHACA, N.Y., June 12. -- In their first hard four-mile row against time on Lake Cayuga on Friday, the Cornell Varsity crew did so well that Coach Courtney gave them a vacation to-day and there was no final practice before the crews left for Poughkeepsie to-night. Coach Courtney would give out no time on last night's performance, but stated that it was "first rate," and that "the crew rowed fine."

abstract: It is a great pleasure to read the interesting and scientifically exact accounts of the beloved gyascutus. Permit me to add that this animal is undoubtedly a member of the deer family, of which J. Caesar writes in the sadly neglected sixth book of the "Gallic War." abstract: GREEN BAY, Wis., June 13. -- One man was killed, two were probably mortally injured, and fourteen others were hurt this morning in the small Catholic church at Bay Settlement, a fishing point north of here on the Green Bay shore. abstract: PITTSBURG, June 13. -- The buying of rails has been the principal item of interest in the steel industry, and inquiries for a greater tonnage have been made which indicate that rail-buying from now on will be far ahead of that of the first six months of the Year. abstract: WESTFIELD, Mass., June 14. -- James Brown Hazelton is one of Westfield's wealthiest citizens. He and Mrs. Hazelton are relatives by marriage, and Mrs. Hazelton is five years older than Mr. Hazelton, who says he is 71, and looks it. Hazelton owns a well-appointed, home in Mill Street. His housekeeper was amazed to-night when told of her employer's matrimonial venture.

abstract: The southeast corner of Fulton and Nassau Streets has been sold by M. Kayser for the estate of Dorothea Wolff to Gyulo Armeny. The property consists of an eight-story building, known as 92 Nassau Street and 126 Fulton Street, 31.2 by 51. The present deal involves only the land, Mr. Armeny having owned the building for several years and held a lease of the site.

abstract: MEADVILLE, Miss., June 14. -- Two men are dead, two were perhaps mortally wounded, and three others slightly injured in a street battle this afternoon waged by parties to a bitter feud that had been previously marked with tragedy. abstract: BOSTON, Mass., June 14. -- Cleveland took the third straight game from Boston to-day, 3 to 1, errors being responsible for every run scored. Joss and Arellanes pitched strongly, the latter allowing but three hits. President John I. Taylor of the local club announced after the game that Chester L. Nourse, the Brown University pitcher, signed a contract with Boston to-day and with report to Manager Lake Thursday.

abstract: PITTSBURG, June 14. -- The children of Pittsburg who have not been so fortunate as Miss Helen Frick has been will enjoy part of the young lady's great wealth. abstract: The treatment of the strike of the Post Office employes in France has taken quite an unexpected turn. abstract: BOSTON, Mass., June 17. -- An accident to his opponent in the first set gave F.J. Sulloway of Franklin, N.H., the final match against C.F. Johnson of this city in the Massachusetts tennis championship at the Longwood Cricket Club to-day. Sulloway will meet R.C. Seaver of Boston in the challenge match to-morrow. Sulloway and Johnson were four games all in first set, when Johnson sprained his ankle and was forced to retire.

abstract: WILLIAMSPORT, Penn., June 18. -- Albert Munro and his bride of a week were found dead in their room this afternoon. On a dresser was a partially filled box of chocolates. abstract: LLANDRINDOD WELLS, Wales, June 10. -- The body of St. John Hankin, author and dramatist, was found yesterday in the River Ithon, near here. Mr. Hankin disappeared from a sanitarium at Llandrindod Wells ten days ago. He was in ill-health and depressed, and left a letter to his wife ending with these words: "I have found a lovely pool in a river, and at the bottom I hope to find rest."

abstract: NEW HAVEN, Conn., June 19. -- Yale found Capt. Caldwell, Cornell's best pitcher, to their liking, and pounded him out of the box in the fourth inning today, scoring six runs and whitewashing the Ithacans. Capt. abstract: GARY, Ind., June 19. -- Frauno Abolpo, who is said to be a member of the Black Hand Society, was shot and probably mortally injured by James Sorreullo here to-day. Abolpo entered Sorreullo's place of business with a note in his hand, which he gave to Sorreullo. The note demanded a certain sum of money to be paid within five days on penalty of the death of Sorreullo and his wife.

abstract: BOSTON, Mass., June 19. -- The locals won from Philadelphia to-day, 7 to 6, in a heavy hitting contest. abstract: OXFORD, Mass., June 20. -- A constable and a burglar are dead as the result of a fight in a railroad waiting station at Oxford Heights, a suburb of this city, at about 3 o'clock this morning. abstract: An attempt to blow up the Italian Roman Catholic Church and school of the Parish of St. Rocco, in Bedford Street, Newark, shortly after 2 o'clock yesterday morning, failed when the fuse attached to one of two tomato cans filled with dynamite missed fire. abstract: VIENNA, June 21. -- There is no truth whatever in the reports, which seem to have been current in many parts of the world, that E.H. Harriman is seriously ill. abstract: MORRISTOWN, N.J., June 21. -- Daniel W. Langton, a landscape artist with offices at 341 Fifth Avenue, New York, committed suicide last night at his home at Hoyt's Corner, three miles from this place. Dr. George L. abstract: Three persons died yesterday as a result of the heat, and four others were taken to hospitals, prostrated by the heat. abstract: PITTSBURG, June 22. -- Pittsburg learned to-day that on last Saturday Samuel Dempster, a member of an old family, had married Miss Jennie Roberts, head milliner in one of the largest establishments in Pittsburg. abstract: Many prostrations, one death by accident, and one suicide make up yesterday's heat record in this city. abstract: Nearly 100,000 Germans went down to Ulmer Park, Brooklyn, yesterday to celebrate with a picnic the close of the Saengerfest which the Northeastern Federation of Singing Societies of America have been holding for the last week at the Madison Square Garden. abstract: COBRE, Nev., June 23. -- The wind and heat prevented me from getting to Tecoma until quite late last night. I left Tecoma at 7:45 this morning, with a gradual increase in the temperature, arriving at Noble, twelve miles, at 11:20 A.M. I will stop here until evening, when I expect the wind to subside and the temperature to fall, as it did last night.

abstract: TANGIER, Morocco, June 23. -- Advices received here from Fez indicate that the internal peace of Morocco is again threatened by the depredations of the rebel Roghi, to whom a large number of the tribes are said to be swearing allegiance. Another factor is the series of raids conducted by the Sultan's rebellious brother Mulai Kebir, who, at the head of the Zeppour tribesmen, is now marching on Mequinez.

abstract: It is more than twice as long since the Revolution as since the Rebellion, yet the Rebellion is the more forgiven and forgotten of the two unpleasantnesses. abstract: BERLIN, June 24. -- The Reichstag added to the Government's difficulties in its proposed financial reforms to-day by rejecting, by a vote of 194 to 186, the Imperial Ministry's bill to extend inheritance taxes to direct heirs, including widows and children. The President of the Reichstag announced this evening that the bill in its present form would be dropped.

abstract: Unwept, unhonored, and unstrung, the wearers of the black went back to Boston yesterday, leaving a sadly disfigured pair of twins on the doorstep of the Giants. It was another day of mourning for the Orphans. abstract: SYRACUSE, June 24. -- Edgar C. Pettie, father-in-law of Oscar Lewisohn, expressed the opinion to-night that his son-in-law was not touring Europe. abstract: WASHINGTON, June 24. -- The Government is contemplating a new venture, the manufacture of ice for the use of the various departments. abstract: PHILADELPHIA, June 25. -- Stallings's Hilltoppers this afternoon dragged the Athletics out of second place in the pennant procession. They pounded Dygert and Vickers all over the meadow for a total of fifteen hits, including two doubles and three triples, and won by a score of 12 to 2. Connie Mack used fourteen men in fruitless efforts to overcome the Toppers, who went through the game with the original nine.

abstract: LONDON, June 18. -- Prof. J. Wight Duff of Newcastle is the author of a "Literary History of Rome," which Unwin publishes before the end of this month. It comprises a sketch of the earliest Latin records of intellectual activity found in inscriptions and a systematic account of the later development of the Latin literature, with constant regard to its relation to the political and social life of the Romans.

abstract: WASHINGTON, June 25. -- Dissatisfied with the manner in which their engine is working, the Wright brothers made no attempt at a flight in their aeroplane today. abstract: Not long ago the Merchants' Association "mugged" the typhoid fly. abstract: A funnel-shaped cloud appeared on the horizon far to the south yesterday afternoon, and at the same time two densely black clouds began to form in the east and west. Slowly the clouds rose in the sky until they seemed about to meet.

abstract: SIR OLIVER LODGE has written a most entertaining book* on the fascinating branch of physics he terms "The Ether of Space." What is this ether which pervades an space, penetrating between the molecules of matter, and even between the atoms in the molecules? We cannot see, hear, feel, taste, smell, exhaust, or weigh it, and yet all this, paradoxical as it may seem, furnishes no proof that it does not exist.

abstract: One thing which some of the old-time conservative element does not like about the stock market is the large number of "good things" which are being passed around. abstract: ASBURY PARK, N.J., June 26. -- This week's sizzling weather, the brand most desired by seashore hotel men, sent an army of newcomers to Asbury Park, and the resort to-night, for the first time this Summer, is filled with pleasure seekers. Despite the intense heat, the visitors found the many beach resorts delightfully cool, and most of them spent their waking hours on the strand.

abstract: IF every woman realized the blessed art of keeping quiet when it is necessary for her health to do so she would be a wiser and stronger woman. abstract: LONG BRANCH, N.J., June 26. -Scores of Summer residents and trainload after trainload of weekend visitors arrived here yesterday and to-day, seeking relief by the seaside from the oppressively warm weather which prevailed this week. abstract: PHILADELPHIA, June 26. -- Connie Mack's cool cards hogged a double-header with Stallings's tribe this afternoon, shutting out the Yankees 3 to 0 in the first game and beating them by 4 to 1 in the second. Big Chief Bender handled the hide for the Athletics in the opening contest, Quinn going through the motions for the Hilltoppers. In the second struggle Coombs curled against Hughes, who was supplanted by Brockett for the eighth.

abstract: FAR ROCKAWAY, L.I., June 26. -- The Temple Israel Fair, one of the first big charitable events of the season, which has been in progress at Horton Hall since last Monday, came to an end to-night. The fan was well patronized, and the building fund, for which the event was promoted, will be considerably benefited. Many pretty young women were incharge of the various booths, and they worked hard to make the fair a success.

abstract: NOAH has been called a Babylonian myth, a sun god, the son of the "Splendor of the Sunset," the second father of mankind, the second Adam. abstract: NEW LONDON, Conn., June 27. -- The steam yacht Christabel, owned by Walter Ferguson of Fisher's Island, took Yale's rowing squad on a three-hour excursion across Long Island Sound and back this morning. The yacht Rosalie, chartered for a few days by former Secretary of State Robert Bacon, was also used as an excursion boat, and a five hours' trip was also made on the Sound, the oarsmen leaving camp at 11:30 o'clock this morning.

COBB of the United States Public Health and Marine Hospital Service is of the opinion that baldness is not congenital, excepting, possibly, in cases where the son inherits his father's lofty brow; that it is not due to dandruff, to parasites, or to any skin disease, and that the hair follicles, once atrophied, cannot be restored. The sole cause of baldness is the constricting bands of hats.

abstract: PARIS, June 29. -- Signor Gugnermo Ferrero, the Italian historian who visited the United States last year, continues the publication in the Figaro to-day of his comments on the anti-plutocratic movement in America. He calls attention again to the lack of organized resistance on the part of the rich, which he explains by a general recognition on their part that the movement has been provoked by real abuses which must be corrected.

abstract: GREENWICH, Conn., June 29. -- The dreaded brown-tail moth, which for years has been most destructive to the foliage of Eastern Massachusetts, has made its appearance in Rye, just across the line in New York. It has come on shrubbery purchased from a Boston concern by W.W. Cook, general counsel for the Postal Telegraph and Cable Company, who has a place in Rye.
